  "prompt": "Can anyone explain how verb forms are used in German like trinkt, trinkst and trinke?",
  "response": "In German, verb conjugation changes based on the subject (person and number). For the verb \"trinken\" (to drink), here's how it changes:\n\n1st Person Singular (I):\n- ich trinke\n\n2nd Person Singular (you, informal):\n- du trinkst\n\n3rd Person Singular (he/she/it):\n- er/sie/es trinkt\n\n1st Person Plural (we):\n- wir trinken\n\n2nd Person Plural (you all, informal):\n- ihr trinkt\n\n3rd Person Plural (they):\n- sie trinken\n\nFormal \"you\" (singular or plural):\n- Sie trinken\n\nThe changes in the verb ending (-e, -st, -t) depend on the subject's person and number. This helps indicate who is performing the action. The stem of the verb (trink-) remains mostly the same, with only the ending changing.\n\nThis pattern is similar for most regular verbs in German, though some irregular verbs have unique conjugations.",
